{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b3302c9d-9c31-4144-89cb-ba420c6d2ec9","content":"I found **3 performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n### 1. File I/O during evaluation (worst offender)\n**Line 13 of `EvalHeavy.csproj`** — `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` reads a file via a property function at evaluation time. This blocks the MSBuild evaluation pipeline with synchronous disk I/O.\n\n### 2. Expensive recursive glob\n**Line 9** — `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" ...>` forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. Broad `**` globs are a well-known evaluation bottleneck, especially as the repo grows.\n\n### 3. Deep nested import chain\n`EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props` — a 3-level deep import chain. Each import requires MSBuild to resolve the path, open, and parse a new file. Flattening or reducing nesting would help.\n\n**Recommendations:**\n- Replace `ReadAllText` with a build target that runs *after* evaluation.\n- Scope the glob to specific extensions (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or a narrower directory.\n- Flatten the `.props` chain where possible.\n\n> Note: `${backend}` in your prompt appears to be an unresolved variable — I analyzed the project directly using the files on disk.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ce52076f-a9d8-44aa-b246-b929b3da0237","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.\n\nNote: The user mentioned `${backend}` which appears to be an unresolved template variable. I'll just proceed with analyzing the project directly.\n\nHere are the performance issues I can identify:\n\n1. **Deep import chain** (`level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`): 3-level deep nested imports add evaluation overhead as MSBuild must resolve and parse each file.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern** (`**\\*.*`): The `AdditionalFiles` item uses a recursive wildcard glob that scans the entire directory tree. \n\n3. **File I/O during evaluation** (`$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))`): Reading file contents via property functions during evaluation blocks the evaluation pipeline and is a known anti-pattern. The recursive glob and file I/O operations are particularly costly during the evaluation phase.","outputTokens":578},"id":"0ee62509-f977-49ad-b72e-6d2e003c72b9","timestamp":"2026-04-07T16:01:30.970Z","parentId":"3e2edc9b-c152-4d7d-83e8-0d67541e2d0b"}
